9":"1169","1125":"1125","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","um 1140":"about 1140","1100":"1100","25 November 1168":"25 November 1168","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Abensberg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German and Swedish (of German origin): habitational name from a place called as ‘eagle's mountain’ (see   Arend   and   Berg  ), probably Ahrensberg in Mecklenburg. Compare   Darensbourg  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Arend","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Arend</i> of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>arn</i> ‘eagle’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule’."]},{"name":"Darensbourg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Aurore, Camile, Pierre.","Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of German   Arensberg  . It is formed with the French preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, spelled <i>d'</i> before a vowel. This surname is found mainly among African Americans.","History: The progenitor of many of the Darensbourgs was Karl Friedrich Arensberg, a German born in Stettin in Pomerania (today Szczecin in Poland), who arrived in LA in 1721. By 1724, Darensbourg, as he came to be known, was de facto leader of the German colony in LA."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilde von Abensberg was born as the daughter of Gebhard I von Hittenburg-Abensberg and Sophia von Bilburg. She married Egino I von Matsch. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 25 November 1168."},"et":{"–25 November 1168":"–25. november 1168","1125–1186":"1125–1186","–1168":"–1168","–1200":"–1200","1120–1192":"1120–1192","1140–1214":"1140–1214","1161–Male":"1161–Surnud","1095–1169":"1095–1169","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1120":"1120","1186":"1186","1140":"1140","1161":"1161","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","1192":"1192","12